Lab Assignment Seven: Recurrent Network Architectures¶

Team members: Long Zhang,Qinyu Chen, Zhengwen Zhang

Business understanding¶

In this lab, We will select a text SMS dataset and perform spam message predictions, We will evaluate a recurrent architecture(LSTM and GRU) and tune hyper-parameters. The SMS Spam Collection is available from kaggle, the downloaded file is in csv format, each line of the SMS is in txt format. The corpus(dataset) is a set of SMS tagged messages that have been collected for free from internet for SMS Spam research. The SMS messages are in English, they are categorized as ham (legitimate) or spam.We think it is a perfect dataset to perform binary classification in Rrcurrent Network.

We think wireless provider will be interested in our prediction model. As we all know that consumers receive tons of spam SMS everyday, this will even cost some charges for some prepaid users in the US, spam SMS messages can also lead to financial loss, unlike legimigate SMS, spam messages can not be unsubscribed most of the time. Based on the results of our model, Service provider can selectively block or filter these messages in the backend before delivering the messages to customers, thus improving quality of mobile services.App developer may also be interested in our model, they can develop apps that implement some algorithms based on our model, end users can block or filter spam SMSs as well.

Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/sms-spam-collection-dataset

The tokenizer class from Keras will convert a text document into a list of integers where each integer represents a word. In this representation, the integer is called a token. In our implementation, we use every word found in all of the documents. We also found the number of words from each document to only the first 400, only very few samples has the extreme long length, we choose to ignore those few extremes.If a document does not have 400 words, then it is zero-padded on the left. The tokens also only represent words-- the punctuation is completely scrubbed from the documents.

1.2 Evaluation Metric¶

Let's see our case, we want to predict what kind of a given text would be -- it's spam or ham? it's a binary classification probelm, and also we notice that the size of each class is imbalanced ( ham size is 4825, spam size is 747).

In this particular imbalanced class problem, if we don't choose a more objective metrics, if the penalty for small and large data when replacing the training model will be the same, which will lead to more sensitive to the data, and the smaller sample size will cause badly prediction bias. How can we deal with this deviation, so that the model has good prediction results for large and small categories?

first we have the traditional metric--Accuracy / precision: precision directly reflects the performance of our machine learning model. The higher the score, the higher the accuracy of the prediction.

second we have Recall rate: Although the accuracy rate is very common, it also has great limitations when facing the problem of class imbalance. Note that recall rate is actually TPR (true positive rate), which is imapcted by the ratio between the predicted positive sample and the true positive sample.

Through the previous analysis, we can find that the precision rate and the recall rate have their own respective emphases, resulting in completely different evaluation results for the same problem, so whether there is a scoring method that can fully consider Accuracy and recall rate, so as to comprehensively evaluate various machine learning models (including class imbalance problems)? The answer is the F1 score.

F1 score formula is fairly simple ---- ( F1 = (2 PRE RECALL) / (PRE + RECALL)). just take the precision rate and recall rate calculated into the f1 formula, the we could get the f1 score.

Generally speaking, especially in the problem of class imbalance, we think that the higher the F1 score, the better the model performance.

referece sorce: python machine learning 3rd

Guglielmocamporese. Macro F1-Score Keras. Kaggle, Kaggle, 20 Oct. 2018, https://www.kaggle.com/guglielmocamporese/macro-f1-score-keras.

In [9]:
import keras.backend as K
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import math

def f1(y_true, y_pred):
    y_pred = K.round(y_pred)
    tp = K.sum(K.cast(y_true*y_pred, 'float'), axis=0)
    # tn = K.sum(K.cast((1-y_true)*(1-y_pred), 'float'), axis=0)
    fp = K.sum(K.cast((1-y_true)*y_pred, 'float'), axis=0)
    fn = K.sum(K.cast(y_true*(1-y_pred), 'float'), axis=0)

    p = tp / (tp + fp + K.epsilon())
    r = tp / (tp + fn + K.epsilon())

    f1 = 2*p*r / (p+r+K.epsilon())
    f1 = tf.where(tf.math.is_nan(f1), tf.zeros_like(f1), f1)
    return K.mean(f1)

2. Modeling¶

LSTM¶

The main hyperparemeters that we experimented with were dropout and recurrent dropout. Dropout refers to the fact that part of the neural network is not being trained on each iteration. We found that when dropout was less than 0.5, there was significant overfitting the performance was subpar. We used the values 0.2, 0.3, 0.4, and 0.5. We also experimented with the size of the unit as we used 32, 64, 128. However, we did not try every combination of size of unit with dropout values. However, we did find decent performance (speed and loss value) when size was 32.

EMBED_SIZE = 100
# the embed size should match the file you load glove from
embeddings_index = {}
#f = open('/Users/terrence/desktop/glove.6B.100d.txt')
#f = open(r'E:\Dropbox\smu\CSE7324\assignment\Lab7\glove.6B.100d.txt')

f = open('/Users/chenqinyu/Desktop/glove.6B/glove.6B.100d.txt', encoding='utf-8')

# save key/array pairs of the embeddings
#  the key of the dictionary is the word, the array is the embedding
for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()

print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

# now fill in the matrix, using the ordering from the
#  keras word tokenizer from before
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be all-zeros.
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector

print(embedding_matrix.shape)

from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense
from keras.layers import LSTM

rnn = Sequential()
rnn.add(embedding_layer)
rnn.add(LSTM(32,dropout=0.5, recurrent_dropout=0.5,activation='relu',return_sequences=True))
rnn.add(GlobalMaxPool1D())
#rnn.add(LSTM(128,dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2,activation='relu'))
rnn.add(Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid'))
rnn.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
              optimizer= 'adam', 
              metrics=['accuracy',f1])
print(rnn.summary())

from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold

n_folds = 10
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=n_folds)

cv_training_f1_score = []
cv_training_loss = []

cv_val_f1_score = []
cv_val_loss = []


iternum = 1
for train_indices, val_indices in skf.split(X_train, y_train):
    X_tmp_train = X_train[train_indices]
    y_tmp_train = y_train_ohe[train_indices]
    
    X_tmp_val = X_train[val_indices]
    y_tmp_val = y_train_ohe[val_indices]
    history = rnn.fit(X_tmp_train, y_tmp_train, validation_data=(X_tmp_val,y_tmp_val), epochs=10, batch_size=64)
    # save the performance data of different training and validation set
    
    cv_training_f1_score.append(history.history.get('f1'))
    cv_val_f1_score.append(history.history.get('val_f1'))
    
    cv_training_loss.append(history.history.get('loss'))
    cv_val_loss.append(history.history.get('val_loss'))

In [16]:
def confusion_rnn(rnn, X_test, y_test_ohe, title):
    yhat = np.argmax(rnn.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    y_test = np.argmax(y_test_ohe, axis = 1)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat)
    cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
    acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, yhat)
    f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_test, yhat, average="macro")
    plt.title("Using " + str(title) + ": " +' Acc: {:.4f}'.format(acc) + ' F1: {:.4f}'.format(f1))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
    plt.show()

Sudalairajkumar. A Look at Different Embeddings.! Kaggle, Kaggle, 8 Nov. 2018, https://www.kaggle.com/sudalairajkumar/a-look-at-different-embeddings.

#Search for the threshold for best f1
def threshold_search(y_true, y_proba):
    best_threshold = 0
    best_score = 0
    for threshold in tqdm([i * 0.01 for i in range(100)], disable=True):
        score = metrics.f1_score(y_true, (y_proba> threshold).astype(int),average = "macro")
        if score > best_score:
            best_threshold = threshold
            best_score = score
    search_result = {'threshold': best_threshold, 'f1': best_score}
    return search_result


test_pred = np.argmax(rnn.predict([X_test], batch_size=512, verbose=1),axis=1)

GRU¶

The main hyperparemeters that we experimented with were dropout and recurrent dropout. Dropout refers to the fact that part of the neural network is not being trained on each iteration. We found that when dropout was more than 0.3, our performance began to get worse. We used the values 0.1, 0.2, and 0.5. We also experimented with the size of the unit as we used 32, 64, 128. However, we did not try every combination of size of unit with dropout values. However, we did find decent performance (speed and loss value) when size was 32.

Then we use 10-fold cross validation to train and investigate the general performance of the chosen model like we talked about.

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
n_folds = 10
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=n_folds)

cv_training_f1_score = []
cv_training_loss = []

cv_val_f1_score = []
cv_val_loss = []


iternum = 1
for train_indices, val_indices in skf.split(X_train, y_train):
    X_tmp_train = X_train[train_indices]
    y_tmp_train = y_train_ohe[train_indices]
    
    X_tmp_val = X_train[val_indices]
    y_tmp_val = y_train_ohe[val_indices]
    history = rnn_gru.fit(X_tmp_train, y_tmp_train, validation_data=(X_tmp_val,y_tmp_val), epochs=10, batch_size=64)
    # save the performance data of different training and validation set
    
    cv_training_f1_score.append(history.history.get('f1'))
    cv_val_f1_score.append(history.history.get('val_f1'))
    
    cv_training_loss.append(history.history.get('loss'))
    cv_val_loss.append(history.history.get('val_loss'))

Adjust hyper-parameters of the networks as needed to improve generalization performance¶

Use different dropout and recurrent dropout list for LSTM and GRU

In [28]:
type_list = [LSTM]
units_list = [32, 64]
dropout_list = [0.4, 0.5]
recurrent_dropout_list = [0.4,0.5]
rnn_list = {}

for (t, u, d, r) in itertools.product(type_list, units_list, dropout_list, recurrent_dropout_list):
    rnn = Sequential()
    rnn.add(embedding_layer)
    rnn.add(t(u,dropout=d, recurrent_dropout=r,activation='relu',return_sequences=True))
    rnn.add(GlobalMaxPool1D())

Discuss the performance of each network nd compare them.¶

Best records for LSTM and GRU:¶

LSTM: unit=32, dropout=0.4, recurrent=0.4): Acc=0.9668161434977578, F1=0.9222907236729334
GRU: unit=32, dropout=0.2, recurrent=0.1): Acc=0.9641255605381166, F1=0.9167823503948174

GRU couples forget as well as input gates. GRU use less training parameters and therefore use less memory, execute faster and train faster than LSTM's whereas LSTM is more accurate on dataset using longer sequence. In short, if sequence is large or accuracy is very critical, please go for LSTM whereas for less memory consumption and faster operation go for GRU. If you donot have much floating point operations per second (FLOP's) to spare switch to GRU. LSTM has three values at output (output, hidden and cell) whereas GRU has two values at output (output and hidden).
Citation from https://www.quora.com/Whats-the-difference-between-LSTM-and-GRU.

From the results got from the LSTM and GRU, we could tell that, LSTM has way better F1 score than GRU, tho the accuracy rate is about the same, but F1 score is more authentic to compare models in our case. Although GRU may run little faster than LSTM, LSTM do not have poor results(F1<0.5) which GRU has. Therefore, we would recommend you to use LSTM to predict imbalanced class data.
